<section id="easterncape">
  <h2>The Eastern Cape Paradox</h2>
  <p>
    High distinctions coexist with the lowest overall pass rate, revealing excellence trapped in
    pockets while failure spreads systemically.
  </p>
  <div class="image-placeholder">Insert provincial comparison table or heat map</div>
  <div class="quote">
    Averages hide pain. Provinces do not fail evenly.
  </div>
</section>

<section id="maths">
  <h2>The Quiet Retreat from Mathematics</h2>
  <p>
    Declining Mathematics enrolment protects short term pass rates while quietly narrowing the
    country’s future skills base.
  </p>
  <div class="image-placeholder">Insert Maths enrolment trend graph</div>
</section>

<section id="economy">
  <h2>Education Without Absorption</h2>
  <p>
    More Bachelor passes enter an economy unable to absorb them, transforming education from an
    equaliser into a sorting mechanism.
  </p>
  <div class="image-placeholder">Insert Bachelor passes vs youth unemployment chart</div>
</section>

<section id="ai">
  <h2>AI and Uneven Advantage</h2>
  <p>
    Artificial intelligence assisted some learners, but amplified inequality rather than repairing
    foundational weaknesses.
  </p>
  <div class="image-placeholder">Insert AI learning illustration</div>
</section>

<section id="conclusion">
  <h2>What the Numbers Refuse to Answer</h2>
  <p>
    The true test of success is not how many pass, but how many are meaningfully absorbed into a
    just and growing society.
  </p>
</section>

